node.text:
I got really into growing tuber or rhizome based crops this year, and I couldn't forget the Jerusalem artichoke, Earth apple, sunchoke, or the appropriately named fartichoke 💨 😂

if you've had trouble growing other tuber style crops before, these will be by far the easiest you'll ever grow. so easy that I highly recommend planting them in a container or else you're going to be growing them for the rest of your natural born life 😭

They can be eaten in just about any way that food can be eaten, with the most common probably being roasting them. To me they taste sort of like a watercress mixed with some kind of light nutty flavor, and don't eat too many or you will absolutely pay the price 😂

node.text:
The great bean debate! Should you direct sow beans, or is it OK to transplant them? We ran a small experiment here at the Epic Homestead. The beans on the left were transplanted after growing for two weeks in Epic 6-Cell Trays (available on store). The beans on the right were direct sown in the bed.

Here's what we noticed: The transplanted beans DID produce quicker, but they also took about ten days to get over the initial transplant shock. The leaves yellowed for a bit, then darkened back up and new green leaves started to grow. I suspect this is due to the roots having 0 access to nitrogen in the beginning of the transplant.

The direct sown beans rocketed up in growth and almost match the transplanted beans in overall plant size, but are about 7 days behind the transplanted beans as far as bean production. HOWEVER, that is a gain of a week on the "true age" of the transplanted beans! 

Direct sowing is my preferred choice, but I can still see reasons to transplant: maximizing bed yield, space considerations, etc.

What do you do?

node.text: I love garden tools...so much so that I probably have about 40 in my shed right now. But as a beginner, you only need about 3 - a cutting tool, digging tool, and watering tool. As you expand your garden, you may want to get into long-handled tools or specialty tools, so I've also included those in this video. At the end, a bit of a bonus on how I sharpen my tools to keep them working for years and years.

node.text:
Honored and humbled to bring you this collaboration with @charles_dowding - we released the full version on YouTube, including Zoom conversations with each other before and after building our no-dig beds. The idea was, "How do you build a no-dig bed based on your unique climate?"

You'll see some differences in approach between myself and Charles, though I will say most of the differences are missteps in my technique - Charles has perfected his methods and in the video you'll see me note the adjustments I'll be making on future beds.

I truly hope this helps you kick off the new year feeling empowered to start growing a bit of your own food, even if you don't have much in the way of resources to buy "fancy" garden products.

Keep on growing,
Kevin

node.title: How to Build a No-Dig Bed with Charles Dowding

node.text: To up your seed starting success rate, try these two tips from Brijette at @sandiegoseedcompany - 1. BOTTOM WATER for stable moisture levels in your seed starting medium. 2. SURFACE SOW and sprinkle seed starting mix over the top to barely cover your seeds.

node.text:
SEEDS - When I first started gardening, I had no idea how many different "types" of seeds there were. This breakdown is far from a detailed list, but hopefully it's a helpful summary on seed terminology and what it actually means.

You'll find that it's still somewhat confusing! For example, there is no set definition that "makes" a seed an heirloom, it's mostly the fact that the variety has been preserved for multiple generations. Some say it's 50 years to qualify, some say 100...it's nebulous!

Likewise with GMO. Many seed packets you can buy will say "non-GMO", but that's like me selling you some water that says "gluten-free". It's ALMOST impossible for a home gardener to purchase true GMO crops, so using "non-GMO" on a seed packet for home gardeners is pure marketing.

For hybrids, it seems their name makes people a little suspicious, despite the fact that hybrid seeds are created from traditional breeding techniques that can take decades (the Clancy potato, a potato you grow from seed took over 20 years to breed). That said, buying hybrid often means you are buying the same seeds year after year, as they're not stable varieties. If you save the seed it's highly unlikely they'll grow "true to type" the next year.

There's a lot more to say here, especially around "organic vs. non-organic" but lemme hear from you - what types of seeds do you grow  in your garden? 👀 ⬇️

EASY BED TRANSFORMATION - When I moved into the Epic Homestead, the landscaping was lackluster to say the LEAST. Over the last year I've been building out the gardens and neglecting a spot in the front yard that was seriously under-loved. I joined @loweshomeimprovement and invited @jacquesinthegarden to help me refresh the front yard bed:

First, we cleaned out the bed, removing weeds and dead plants. Next, a sprinkling of fertilizer across the entire surface of the soil, then it was digging time.

The soil was surprisingly tough, so digging holes and filling with water, then digging again after an hour or two was the method we went with.

We selected Dipladenia, Angelonia, and Salvia for this bed - easy care options that will grow in nicely over time.

Finally, edging and mulch was added. The bed is on a slope, so without edging both mulch and water would spill all over the driveway instead of watering and protecting the plants. We used a fine pathway bark product from Lowe's instead of a more standard mulch, as I love the appearance and performance of fine bark.

Want to try it out yourself? Be sure to share and tag @loweshomeimprovement and #FallTogether! #LowesPartner

🌻 SUNFLOWER SECRETS 🌻 Native to North America, sunflowers are a garden staple. But there is so much more to them than just the large flower heads!

First, that flowerhead is actually two types of flowers. First you have the ray flowers which of the large petals on the exterior, then you have the disc flowers which are on the interior and are pollinated to produce the sunflower seeds.

Second, did you know that you can actually eat an entire sunflower head!? I found out about it recently and I’m going to try it over on @epichomesteading YouTube channel soon.

Long story short, plant some of these bad boys in your garden ASAP, even if you only scatter them around is a cover crop.

Comment your fav variety 👀 ⬇️

PINK PINEAPPLES - Until a week ago I never knew these existed! The color is absolutely striking and it is a bit sweeter than the average golden pineapple.

But how was this created? It is an example of an actual GMO crop, where the pineapple was bioengineered two mute an enzyme which converts lycopene into beta carotene, which is what gives a pineapple the golden color. This means that the pineapple stays this reddish pink color!

If you ever buy one of these, you’ll notice that it never comes with a top. The reason for this, despite the marketing claim of sustainability, is so that no one else besides the grower is able to propagate it, because they spent 16 years developing it and they want to protect their crop.

This is a very interesting example of the business behind plants that many of us might not be aware of. I’d love to know what you think about something like this in the comments, I know it can be quite divisive! ⬇️

node.text:
STARTING A RAISED BED GARDEN - I've built 3 raised bed gardens from scratch for myself, and a few for others like @kehlani - here are 3 mistakes to avoid so you don't spend a lot of $ and time, only to get poor results. P.S. I'VE MADE THEM ALL MYSELF 😂

1️⃣ SOIL - Without a doubt the #1 way I see gardeners go wrong. You want the highest quality soil you can POSSIBLY afford starting out. Whether you purchase it in bulk, bags, or make it yourself, quality is king here. If you're making it yourself, either go with Mel's Mix, or a mixture of 50% native topsoil, 25% compost, and 25% other organic matter (leaves, grass clippings, etc.) is a solid mixture. I recommend hunting around locally for bulk soil delivery that's quality...your dollar will go MUCH further.

2️⃣ PLACEMENT - There are two main ways you can go wrong with placement. First, you can place your beds too close together, and not be able to access them easily with a wheelbarrow or tools. Second, you can place them in an area that gets poor access to sunlight. Place your garden in an easy to access spot with around 30" of space between beds, and ideally facing S>W>E>N if you're in the northern hemisphere.

3️⃣ NO IRRIGATION - I'm still making this mistake as we speak! I have a @hoselinkusa retractable reel for hand watering, which works just fine, but eventually, I need to install proper drip / soaker lines in the raised bed garden. I consider raised bed irrigation the 'base layer' of watering for the garden - you can still come out and hand water the entire garden if you want to, but it's vital to have a system in place if you're ever on vacation, busy, or it's a really hot day and you need to provide extra water without spending the whole day in the garden.

If you've made one of these mistakes (or another I didn't mention), drop it below so we can all learn from our fails 😂 ⬇
